WEBVTT

00:25.540 --> 00:27.600
CHAPTER XX.

00:30.240 --> 00:31.920
Jonathan Harker's Journal

00:33.420 --> 00:35.680
1st October, Evening

00:37.540 --> 00:41.260
I found Thomas Snelling in his house at Bethnal Green,

00:41.620 --> 00:45.160
but unhappily he was not in a condition to remember anything.

00:46.360 --> 00:50.500
The very prospect of beer which my expected coming had opened to him,

00:50.720 --> 00:55.460
had proved too much, and he had begun too early on his expected debauch.

00:56.140 --> 01:01.260
I learned, however, from his wife, who seemed a decent poor soul,

01:01.920 --> 01:04.200
that he was only the assistant of Smollett,

01:05.100 --> 01:07.760
who of the two mates was the responsible person.

01:08.840 --> 01:13.780
So off I drove to Walworth, and found Mr. Joseph Smollett at home,

01:14.000 --> 01:18.320
and in his shirt sleeves, taking a late tea out of a saucer.

01:18.780 --> 01:24.360
He is a decent, intelligent fellow, distinctly a good, reliable type of workman,

01:24.800 --> 01:26.580
and with a headpiece of his own.

01:27.480 --> 01:30.140
He remembered all about the incident of the boxes,

01:30.880 --> 01:32.840
and from a wonderful dog-eared notebook,

01:33.120 --> 01:37.080
which he produced from some mysterious receptacle about the seat of his trousers,

01:37.960 --> 01:42.220
and which had hieroglyphical entries in thick half-obliterated pencil,

01:43.080 --> 01:45.300
he gave me the destinations of the boxes.

01:46.160 --> 01:50.000
There were, he said, six in the card-load which he took from Carfax,

01:50.000 --> 01:54.120
and left at 197 Chickson Street, Mile End, New Town,

01:54.840 --> 01:58.340
and another six which he deposited at Jamaica Lane, Bermondsey.

01:59.640 --> 02:04.340
If, then, the Count meant to scatter these ghastly refuges of his over London,

02:04.900 --> 02:07.400
these places were chosen as the first of delivery,

02:08.100 --> 02:10.380
so that later he might distribute more fully.

02:11.640 --> 02:15.300
The systematic manner in which this was done made me think that he could not mean

02:15.300 --> 02:17.700
to confine himself to two sides of London.

02:18.460 --> 02:21.820
He was now fixed on the Far East on the Northern Shore,

02:22.060 --> 02:24.740
on the East of the Southern Shore, and on the South.

02:25.700 --> 02:29.840
The North and West were surely never meant to be left out of his diabolical scheme,

02:30.460 --> 02:35.280
let alone the city itself, and the very heart of fashionable London in the South West and West.

02:36.460 --> 02:39.140
I went back to Smollett, and asked him if he could tell us

02:39.140 --> 02:41.540
if any other boxes had been taken from Carfax.

02:42.400 --> 02:43.260
He replied,

02:43.760 --> 02:46.500
Well, Governor, you've treated me very handsome.

02:47.200 --> 02:49.060
I had given him half a sovereign.

02:49.800 --> 02:51.360
And I'll tell you all I know.

02:52.260 --> 02:56.300
I heard a man by the name of Bloxham say four nights ago in the Aire and Ounce,

02:56.580 --> 03:01.820
in Pinchard Alley, as how he and his mate had had a rare dusty job in an old house at Perfleet.

03:02.700 --> 03:04.820
There ain't many such jobs as this here,

03:05.100 --> 03:08.100
and I'm thinking that maybe Sam Bloxham could tell you summat.

03:08.980 --> 03:11.340
I asked if he could tell me where to find him.

03:11.340 --> 03:16.440
I told him that if he could get me the address it would be worth another half sovereign to him.

03:17.500 --> 03:20.160
So he gulped down the rest of his tea and stood up,

03:20.340 --> 03:23.060
saying that he was going to begin the search then and there.

03:23.760 --> 03:25.540
At the door he stopped and said,

03:25.760 --> 03:29.120
Look here, Governor, there ain't no cent in mere keeping you here.

03:29.920 --> 03:32.420
I may find Sam soon, or I mayn't.

03:32.860 --> 03:36.700
But anyhow, he ain't like to be in a way to tell you much to-night.

03:37.760 --> 03:40.160
Sam is a rare one when he starts on the booze.

03:40.900 --> 03:45.360
If you can give me an envelope with a stamp on it, and put your address on it,

03:45.660 --> 03:48.640
I'll find out where Sam is to be found and post at you to-night.

03:49.900 --> 03:53.880
But you'd better be up after him soon in the morning, ever mind the booze the night afore.

03:55.180 --> 03:56.460
This was all practical.

03:57.320 --> 04:01.080
So one of the children went off with a penny to buy an envelope and a sheet of paper,

04:01.420 --> 04:02.700
and to keep the change.

04:03.800 --> 04:06.940
When she came back I addressed the envelope and stamped it,

04:06.940 --> 04:10.900
and when Smollett had again faithfully promised to post the address when found,

04:11.040 --> 04:12.300
I took my way to home.

04:13.280 --> 04:14.800
We're on the track anyhow.

04:15.780 --> 04:18.780
I am tired to-night, and I want to sleep.

04:20.000 --> 04:22.840
Mina is fast asleep, and looks a little too pale.

04:24.060 --> 04:26.100
Her eyes look as though she had been crying.

04:27.280 --> 04:30.360
Poor dear, I've no doubt it frets her to be kept in the dark.

04:31.340 --> 04:34.300
And it may make her doubly anxious about me and the others.

04:35.300 --> 04:37.240
But it is best as it is.

04:38.940 --> 04:43.460
It is better to be disappointed and worried in such a way now than to have her nerve broken.

04:44.580 --> 04:48.440
The doctors were quite right to insist on her being kept out of this dreadful business.

04:49.740 --> 04:54.100
I must be firm, for on me this particular burden of silence must rest.

04:55.540 --> 04:59.660
I shall not ever enter on the subject with her under any circumstances.

05:00.800 --> 05:06.960
Indeed, it may not be a hard task, after all, for she herself has become reticent on the subject,

05:07.660 --> 05:12.460
and has not spoken of the Count or his doings ever since we told her of our decision.

05:15.200 --> 05:21.000
Second October. Evening. A long and trying and exciting day.

05:22.340 --> 05:26.740
By the first post I got my directed envelope with a dirty scrap of paper enclosed,

05:26.740 --> 05:30.280
on which was written with a carpenter's pencil in a sprawling hand,

05:31.040 --> 05:39.060
Sam Bloxham, Corcoran's, 4 Poters Court, Bartle Street, Walworth. Ask for the dip height.

05:40.680 --> 05:43.740
I got the letter in bed and rose without waking Mina.

05:44.720 --> 05:48.020
She looked heavy and sleepy and pale and far from well.

05:48.860 --> 05:53.820
I determined not to wake her, but that when I should return from this new search

05:53.820 --> 05:56.300
I would arrange for her going back to Exeter.

05:57.320 --> 06:02.720
I think she would be happier in our own home with her daily tasks to interest her,

06:03.000 --> 06:05.220
than in being here amongst us and in ignorance.

06:06.660 --> 06:10.920
I only saw Dr Seward for a moment and told him where I was off to,

06:11.540 --> 06:15.440
promising to come back and tell the rest so soon as I should have found out anything.

06:17.160 --> 06:21.020
I drove to Walworth and found, with some difficulty, Potter's Court.

06:22.080 --> 06:27.060
Mr Smollett's spelling misled me, as I asked for Poters Court instead of Potter's Court.

06:28.160 --> 06:32.980
However, when I had found the court I had no difficulty in discovering Corcoran's lodging

06:32.980 --> 06:39.740
house. When I asked the man who came to the door for the dip height, he shook his head and said,

06:40.400 --> 06:46.280
I don't know him. There ain't no such person here. I never heard of him in all my blooming days.

06:47.060 --> 06:50.360
Don't believe there ain't nobody of that kind living here or anywheres.

06:51.420 --> 06:56.160
I took out Smollett's letter, and as I read it, it seemed to me that the lesson of the spelling of

06:56.160 --> 07:00.660
the name of the court might guide me. What are you? I asked.

07:01.820 --> 07:06.820
I'm the deputy, he answered. I saw at once that I was on the right track.

07:08.240 --> 07:14.000
Phonetic spelling had again misled me. A half-crowned tip put the deputy's knowledge at my

07:14.000 --> 07:19.600
disposal, and I learned that Mr Bloxham, who had slept off the remains of his beer on the previous

07:19.600 --> 07:25.640
night at Corcoran's, had left for his work at Poplar at five o'clock that morning. He could not

07:25.640 --> 07:31.180
tell me where the place of work was situated, but he had a vague idea that it was some kind of a

07:31.180 --> 07:38.300
newfangled warress, and with this slender clue I had to start for Poplar. It was twelve o'clock

07:38.300 --> 07:43.520
before I got any satisfactory hint of such a building, and this I got at a coffee shop,

07:43.800 --> 07:49.520
where some workmen were having their dinner. One of them suggested that there was being erected

07:49.520 --> 07:56.200
cross Angel Street a new cold storage building, and as this suited the condition of a newfangled

07:56.200 --> 08:03.420
warress, I at once drove to it. An interview with a surly gatekeeper and a surlier foreman,

08:04.140 --> 08:09.160
both of whom were appeased with the coin of the realm, put me on the track of Bloxham.

08:10.800 --> 08:15.940
He was sent for on my suggestion that I was willing to pay his day's wages to his foreman

08:15.940 --> 08:19.080
for the privilege of asking him a few questions on a private matter.

08:20.440 --> 08:26.180
He was a smart enough fellow, though rough of speech and bearing. When I had promised to pay

08:26.180 --> 08:31.180
for his information and given him an earnest, he told me that he had made two journeys between

08:31.180 --> 08:37.560
Carfax and a house in Piccadilly, and had taken from this house to the latter nine great boxes,

08:38.380 --> 08:43.440
main heavy ones, with a horse and cart hired by him for this purpose.

08:44.680 --> 08:49.760
I asked him if he could tell me the number of the house in Piccadilly, to which he replied,

08:50.480 --> 08:56.460
Well, Governor, I forgets the number, but it was only a few door from a big white church,

08:56.740 --> 09:02.900
or something of the kind, not long built. It was a dusty old house, too, though nothing to the

09:02.900 --> 09:08.780
dustiness of the house we took the blooming boxes from. How did you get in if both houses were empty?

09:09.660 --> 09:15.380
There was the old party that engaged me awaiting at the house at Purfleet. He helped me to lift the

09:15.380 --> 09:20.520
boxes and put them in the dray, cursed me, but he was the strongest chap I ever struck, and him an

09:20.520 --> 09:24.400
old fellow with a white moustache, one that thin you would think he couldn't throw a shadow.

09:25.340 --> 09:31.460
How this phrase thrilled through me! Why, he took up his end of the boxes like they was pounds of

09:31.460 --> 09:36.560
tea, and me a puffin' and a blowin' afore I could upend mine anyhow, and I'm no chicken neither.

09:37.160 --> 09:40.820
How did you get into the house in Piccadilly? I asked.

09:41.600 --> 09:46.380
He was there, too. He must have started off and got there afore me, for when I rung the bell

09:46.380 --> 09:50.160
he came and opened the door himself, and helped me carry the boxes into the hall.

09:51.080 --> 09:53.340
The whole nine? I asked.

09:54.480 --> 09:57.720
Yes, there was five in the first load and four in the second.

09:58.500 --> 10:01.820
It was main dry work, and I don't so well remember how I got home.

10:02.140 --> 10:05.380
I interrupted him. Were the boxes left in the hall?

10:06.200 --> 10:09.120
Yes, it was a big hall, and there was nothing else in it.

10:10.220 --> 10:14.300
I made one more attempt to further matters. You didn't have any key?

10:15.060 --> 10:19.340
Never used no key nor nothing. The old gent, he opened the door himself,

10:19.420 --> 10:24.120
and shut it again when I drove off. I don't remember the last time, but that was the beer.

10:25.280 --> 10:27.260
And you can't remember the number of the house?

10:28.240 --> 10:31.840
No, sir. But you needn't have no difficulty about that.

10:32.580 --> 10:37.440
It's iron with a stone front with a bow on it, and I steps up to the door.

10:37.840 --> 10:41.640
I know them steps, having had to carry the boxes up with three loafers that come round

10:41.640 --> 10:46.180
to earn a copper. The old gent gave them shillings, and they seeing they got so much,

10:46.240 --> 10:49.960
they wanted more. But he took one of them by the shoulder and was like to throw him

10:49.960 --> 10:52.380
down the steps till the lot of them went away cussing.

10:53.500 --> 10:56.420
I thought that with this description I could find the house.

10:57.100 --> 11:00.660
So having paid my friend for his information, I started off for Piccadilly.

11:01.380 --> 11:06.420
I had gained a new painful experience. The Count could, it was evident,

11:06.800 --> 11:12.640
handle the earth boxes himself. If so, time was precious. For now that he had achieved

11:12.640 --> 11:19.100
a certain amount of distribution, he could, by choosing his own time, complete the task unobserved.

11:20.520 --> 11:24.060
At Piccadilly Circus I discharged my cab and walked westward.

11:25.140 --> 11:29.500
Beyond the junior constitutional, I came across the house described and was satisfied that this

11:29.500 --> 11:34.780
was the next of the layers arranged by Dracula. The house looked as though it had been long

11:34.780 --> 11:41.100
untenanted. The windows were encrusted with dust and the shutters were up. All the framework was

11:41.100 --> 11:47.520
black with time, and from the iron the paint had mostly scaled away. It was evident that up to

11:47.520 --> 11:53.460
lately there had been a large notice board in front of the balcony. It had, however, been roughly

11:53.460 --> 11:57.240
torn away, the uprights which had supported it still remaining.

11:58.640 --> 12:03.340
Behind the rails of the balcony, I saw there were some loose boards whose raw edges looked

12:03.340 --> 12:08.380
white. I would have given a good deal to have been able to see the notice board intact,

12:09.060 --> 12:12.600
as it would, perhaps, have given some clue to the ownership of the house.

12:13.900 --> 12:17.860
I remembered my experience of the investigation and purchase of Carfax,

12:18.220 --> 12:22.600
and I could not but feel that if I could find the former owner there might be some means

12:22.600 --> 12:28.740
discovered of gaining access to the house. There was at present nothing to be learned

12:28.740 --> 12:33.700
from the Piccadilly side, and nothing could be done, so I went around the back to see if

12:33.700 --> 12:39.340
anything could be gathered from this quarter. The mews were active, the Piccadilly houses being

12:39.340 --> 12:45.180
mostly in occupation. I asked one or two of the grooms and helpers whom I saw around if

12:45.180 --> 12:49.880
they could tell me anything about the empty house. One of them said that he heard it had

12:49.880 --> 12:56.500
lately been taken, but he couldn't say from whom. He told me, however, that up to very

12:56.500 --> 13:02.840
lately there had been a notice board of For Sale up, and that perhaps Mitchell, Sons and Candy,

13:02.940 --> 13:07.580
the house agents, could tell me something, as he thought he remembered seeing the name of that firm

13:07.580 --> 13:13.900
on the board. I did not wish to seem too eager or to let my informant know or guess too much,

13:13.900 --> 13:17.480
so thanking him in the usual manner I strolled away.

13:18.920 --> 13:24.760
It was now growing dusk, and the autumn night was closing in, so I did not lose any time.

13:25.300 --> 13:29.460
Having learned the address of Mitchell, Sons and Candy from a directory at the Barclay,

13:29.800 --> 13:36.040
I was soon at their office in Sackville Street. The gentleman who saw me was particularly suave

13:36.040 --> 13:42.780
in manner, but uncommunicative in equal proportion. Having once told me that the Piccadilly house,

13:42.780 --> 13:48.660
which throughout our interview he called a mansion, was sold, he considered my business

13:48.660 --> 13:54.500
as concluded. When I asked who had purchased it, he opened his eyes a thought wider,

13:55.240 --> 13:57.440
and paused a few seconds before replying,

13:58.320 --> 14:00.260
It is sold, sir.

14:01.880 --> 14:07.380
Pardon me, I said, with equal politeness, but I have a special reason for wishing to know who

14:07.380 --> 14:12.820
purchased it. Again he paused longer and raised his eyebrows still more.

14:13.580 --> 14:17.360
It is sold, sir, was again his laconic reply.

14:18.540 --> 14:22.960
Surely, I said, you do not mind letting me know so much.

14:23.880 --> 14:29.140
But I do mind, he answered, the affairs of their clients are absolutely safe in the

14:29.140 --> 14:34.700
hands of Mitchell, Sons and Candy. This was manifestly a prig of the first water,

14:34.700 --> 14:40.380
and there was no use arguing with him. I thought I had best meet him on his own ground,

14:40.740 --> 14:46.720
so I said, Your clients, sir, are happy in having so resolute a guardian of their confidence.

14:47.280 --> 14:55.000
I am myself a professional man. Here I handed him my card. In this instance I am not prompted

14:55.000 --> 15:01.000
by curiosity. I act on the part of Lord Godelming, who wishes to know something of the property which

15:01.000 --> 15:07.500
was, he understood, lately for sale. These words put a different complexion on affairs.

15:08.180 --> 15:13.980
He said, I would like to oblige you if I could, Mr. Harker, and especially would I like to oblige

15:13.980 --> 15:19.660
his lordship. We once carried out a small matter of renting some chambers for him when he was the

15:19.660 --> 15:25.180
Honorable Arthur Homewood. If you will let me have his lordship's address, I will consult the

15:25.180 --> 15:30.220
house on the subject, and will, in any case, communicate with his lordship by tonight's post.

15:31.000 --> 15:35.640
It will be a pleasure if we can so far deviate from our rules as to give the required information

15:35.640 --> 15:42.720
to his lordship. I wanted to secure a friend and not make an enemy, so I thanked him,

15:42.960 --> 15:49.640
gave the address at Dr. Seward's, and came away. It was now dark, and I was tired and hungry.

15:50.560 --> 15:55.380
I got a cup of tea at the aerated bread company, and came down to Purfleet by the next train.

15:56.060 --> 16:01.020
I found all the others at home. Mina was looking tired and pale,

16:01.440 --> 16:06.820
but she made a gallant effort to be bright and cheerful. It rung my heart to think that I had

16:06.820 --> 16:12.640
had to keep anything from her, and so caused her inquietude. Thank God this will be the last night

16:12.640 --> 16:17.780
of her looking on at our conferences, and feeling the sting of our not showing our confidence.

16:18.820 --> 16:23.500
It took all my courage to hold to the wise resolution of keeping her out of our grim task.

16:24.460 --> 16:30.640
She seems somehow more reconciled, or else the very subject seems to have become repugnant to her,

16:31.060 --> 16:34.960
for when any accidental illusion is made, she actually shudders.

16:36.440 --> 16:40.780
I am glad we made our resolution in time, as with such a feeling as this,

16:41.060 --> 16:43.220
our growing knowledge would be torture to her.

16:45.140 --> 16:49.020
I could not tell the others of the day's discovery till we were alone,

16:49.780 --> 16:54.780
so after dinner, followed by a little music to save appearances even amongst ourselves,

16:55.740 --> 16:58.120
I took Mina to her room and left her to go to bed.

16:59.120 --> 17:03.720
The dear girl was more affectionate with me than ever, and clung to me as though she would detain

17:03.720 --> 17:10.000
me. But there was much to be talked of, and I came away. Thank God the ceasing of telling

17:10.000 --> 17:15.400
things has made no difference between us. When I came down again, I found the others

17:15.400 --> 17:20.420
gathered round the fire in the study. In the train I had written my diary so far,

17:20.760 --> 17:25.140
and simply read it off to them as the best means of letting them get a breast of my own information.

17:26.840 --> 17:28.800
When I had finished, Van Helsing said,

17:29.280 --> 17:34.020
This has been a great day's work, friend Jonathan. Doubtless we are on the track

17:34.020 --> 17:39.360
of the missing boxes. If we find them all in that house, then our work is near the end.

17:40.060 --> 17:43.680
But if there be some missing, we must search until we find them,

17:43.680 --> 17:48.060
then surely make our final coup, and hunt the wretch to his real death.

17:49.320 --> 17:52.940
We all sat silent a while, and all at once Mr Norrish spoke.

17:53.860 --> 17:56.180
Say, how are we going to get into that house?

17:56.680 --> 18:00.020
We got into the other, answered Lord Godelman quickly.

18:01.040 --> 18:06.220
But Art, this is different. We broke house at Carfax, but we had night and a walled park

18:06.220 --> 18:10.800
to protect us. It will be a mighty different thing to commit burglary in Piccadilly,

18:10.800 --> 18:15.440
either by day or night. I confess I don't see how we are going to get in,

18:15.460 --> 18:18.300
unless that agency duck can find us a key of some sort.

18:19.820 --> 18:23.840
Lord Godelman's brows contracted, and he stood up and walked about the room.

18:24.840 --> 18:28.580
By and by he stopped and said, turning from one to another of us,

18:29.180 --> 18:32.900
Quincy's head is level, this burglary business is getting serious.

18:33.640 --> 18:37.640
We got off once all right, but we have now a rare job on hand,

18:37.640 --> 18:40.060
unless we can find the Count's key basket.

18:41.660 --> 18:46.460
As nothing could well be done before morning, and as it would be at least advisable to wait

18:46.460 --> 18:51.740
till Lord Godelman should hear from Mitchell's, we decided not to take any active step before

18:51.740 --> 18:57.260
breakfast time. For a good while we sat and smoked, discussing the matter in its various

18:57.260 --> 19:02.300
lights and bearings. I took the opportunity of bringing this diary right up to the moment.

19:03.040 --> 19:10.180
I am very sleepy and shall go to bed. Just a line. Mina sleeps soundly and her breathing is

19:10.180 --> 19:16.620
regular. Her forehead is puckered up into little wrinkles, as though she thinks even in her sleep.

19:17.560 --> 19:23.800
She is still too pale, but does not look so haggard as she did this morning. Tomorrow will,

19:23.800 --> 19:30.700
I hope, mend all this. She will be herself at home in Exeter. Oh, but I am sleepy.

19:33.420 --> 19:42.060
Dr. Seward's Diary. 1st October. I am puzzled afresh about Renfield. His moods change so rapidly

19:42.060 --> 19:47.200
that I find it difficult to keep touch of them. And as they always mean something more than his

19:47.200 --> 19:53.800
own well-being, they form a more than interesting study. This morning, when I went to see him after

19:53.800 --> 20:00.820
his repulse of Van Helsing, his manner was that of a man commanding destiny. He was, in fact,

20:00.820 --> 20:06.900
commanding destiny, subjectively. He did not really care for any of the things of mere earth.

20:07.400 --> 20:11.740
He was in the clouds and looked down on all the weaknesses and wants of us poor mortals.

20:13.260 --> 20:17.320
I thought I would improve the occasion and learn something, so I asked him,

20:17.800 --> 20:25.300
what about the flies these times? He smiled on me in quite a superior sort of way, such a smile as

20:25.300 --> 20:31.860
would have become the face of Malvolio, as he answered me. The fly, my dear sir, has one striking

20:31.860 --> 20:38.740
feature. Its wings are typical of the aerial powers of the psychic faculties. The ancients did well

20:38.740 --> 20:45.020
when they typified the soul as a butterfly. I thought I would push his analogy to its utmost

20:45.020 --> 20:53.340
logically. So I said quickly, oh, it is a soul you are after now, is it? His madness foiled his reason

20:53.340 --> 20:58.380
and a puzzled look spread over his face as, shaking his head with a decision which I had

20:58.380 --> 21:07.540
but seldom seen in him, he said, oh, no, oh, no, I want no souls. Life is all I want. Here he

21:07.540 --> 21:14.460
brightened up. I am pretty indifferent about it at present. Life is all right. I have all I want.

21:15.240 --> 21:21.720
You must get a new patient, doctor, if you wish to study zoophagy. This puzzled me a little,

21:21.720 --> 21:29.400
so I drew him on. Then you command life. You are a god, I suppose. He smiled with an ineffably benign

21:29.400 --> 21:36.100
superiority. Oh, no, far be it from me to arrogate to myself the attributes of the deity.

21:37.060 --> 21:43.020
I am not even concerned in his especially spiritual doings. If I may state my intellectual

21:43.020 --> 21:48.800
position, I am, so far as concerns things purely terrestrial, somewhat in the position which Enoch

21:48.800 --> 21:56.180
occupied spiritually. This was a poser to me. I could not at the moment recall Enoch's

21:56.180 --> 22:02.240
appositeness, so I had to ask a simple question, though I felt that by so doing I was lowering

22:02.240 --> 22:09.140
myself in the eyes of the lunatic. And why with Enoch? Because he walked with God.

22:10.140 --> 22:16.960
I could not see the analogy, but did not like to admit it, so I harked back to what he had denied.

22:17.560 --> 22:24.500
So you don't care about life, and you don't want souls. Why not? I put my question quickly

22:24.500 --> 22:31.540
and somewhat sternly, on purpose to disconcert him. The effort succeeded. For an instant he

22:31.540 --> 22:36.440
unconsciously relapsed into his old servile manner, bent low before me, and actually

22:36.440 --> 22:42.360
fawned upon me as he replied, I don't want any souls, indeed, indeed, I don't. I couldn't use

22:42.360 --> 22:48.980
them if I had them. They would be no manner of use to me. I couldn't eat them, or... He suddenly

22:48.980 --> 22:54.160
stopped, and the old cunning look spread over his face, like a wind sweep on the surface of the water.

22:54.900 --> 22:59.560
And, Doctor, as to life, what is it, after all, when you've got all you require?

23:00.260 --> 23:06.260
And you know that you will never want, that is all. I have friends, good friends, like you,

23:06.260 --> 23:10.540
Doctor Seward. This was said with a leer of inexpressible cunning.

23:11.240 --> 23:17.280
I know that I shall never lack the means of life. I think that through the cloudiness of his insanity

23:17.280 --> 23:23.060
he saw some antagonism in me, for he at once fell back on the last refuge of such as he,

23:23.260 --> 23:29.380
a dogged silence. After a short time I saw that for the present it was useless to speak to him.

23:30.000 --> 23:37.300
He was sulky, and so I came away. Later in the day he sent for me. Ordinarily I would not have

23:37.300 --> 23:42.940
come without special reason, but just at present I am so interested in him that I would gladly make

23:42.940 --> 23:49.980
an effort. Besides, I am glad to have anything to help pass the time. Harker is out, following up

23:49.980 --> 23:56.780
clues, and so are Lord Godelming and Quincy. Van Helsing sits in my study, pouring over the record

23:56.780 --> 24:01.960
prepared by the Harkers. He seems to think that by accurate knowledge of all details he will light

24:01.960 --> 24:08.740
upon some clue. He does not wish to be disturbed in the work without cause. I would have taken him

24:08.740 --> 24:14.020
with me to see the patient. Only I thought that after his last repulse he might not care to go

24:14.020 --> 24:20.760
again. There was also another reason. Renfield might not speak so freely before a third person

24:20.760 --> 24:27.560
as when he and I were alone. I found him sitting in the middle of the floor on his stool,

24:27.940 --> 24:31.620
a pose which is generally indicative of some mental energy on his part.

24:32.680 --> 24:36.680
When I came in he said at once, as though the question had been waiting on his lips,

24:37.460 --> 24:43.720
what about souls? It was evident then that my surmise had been correct.

24:44.760 --> 24:48.380
Unconscious celebration was doing its work, even with the lunatic.

24:49.560 --> 24:56.800
I determined to have the matter out. What about them yourself? I asked. He did not reply for a

24:56.800 --> 25:02.420
moment, but looked all around him, and up and down, as though he expected to find some inspiration

25:02.420 --> 25:10.280
for an answer. I don't want any souls, he said in a feeble apologetic way. The matter seemed

25:10.280 --> 25:16.960
praying on his mind, and so I determined to use it. To be cruel only to be kind. So I said,

25:17.640 --> 25:24.400
you like life and you want life? Oh yes, but that is all right, you needn't worry about that.

25:25.020 --> 25:31.980
But, I asked, how are we to get the life without getting the soul also? This seemed to puzzle him,

25:32.420 --> 25:38.320
so I followed it up. A nice time you'll have some time when you're flying out there with the souls

25:38.320 --> 25:43.000
of thousands of flies and spiders and birds and cats buzzing and twittering and moaning all around

25:43.000 --> 25:49.740
you. You've got their lives, you know, and you must put up with their souls. Something seemed to

25:49.740 --> 25:55.380
affect his imagination, for he put his fingers to his ears and shut his eyes, screwing them up

25:55.380 --> 26:00.900
tightly just as a small boy does when his face is being soaked. There was something pathetic in it

26:00.900 --> 26:08.200
that touched me. It also gave me a lesson, for it seemed that before me was a child, only a child,

26:08.320 --> 26:14.020
though the features were worn and the stubble on the jaws was white. It was evident that he was

26:14.020 --> 26:19.500
undergoing some process of mental disturbance, and knowing how his past moods had interpreted

26:19.500 --> 26:24.420
things seemingly foreign to himself, I thought I would enter into his mind as well as I could

26:24.420 --> 26:31.660
and go with him. The first step was to restore confidence, so I asked him, speaking pretty loud

26:31.660 --> 26:36.220
so that he would hear me through his closed ears, would you like some sugar to get your

26:36.220 --> 26:42.020
eyes around again? He seemed to wake up all at once and shook his head. With a laugh he replied,

26:42.520 --> 26:49.440
not much, flies are poor things after all. After a pause, he added, but I don't want their souls

26:49.440 --> 26:56.300
buzzing round me all the same, or spiders, I went on. Blow spiders, what's the use of spiders?

26:56.980 --> 27:05.440
There isn't anything in them to eat, or he stopped suddenly as though reminded of a

27:05.440 --> 27:09.740
second time he has suddenly stopped at the word drink. What does it mean?

27:12.440 --> 27:17.020
Renfield seemed himself aware of having made a lapse, for he hurried on as though to distract

27:17.020 --> 27:23.820
my attention from it. I don't take any stock at all in such matters. Rats and mice and such small

27:23.820 --> 27:30.020
deer, as Shakespeare has it, chicken feed of the larder, they might be called. I'm past all that

27:30.020 --> 27:35.420
sort of nonsense. You might as well ask a man to eat molecules with a pair of chopsticks, as to

27:35.420 --> 27:42.120
try to interest me about the less carnivora, when I know of what is before me. I see, I said,

27:42.320 --> 27:47.620
you want big things that you can make your teeth meet in. How would you like to breakfast on an

27:47.620 --> 27:53.720
elephant? What ridiculous nonsense you are talking! He was getting too wide awake, so I thought I would

27:53.720 --> 28:01.240
press him hard. I wonder, I said, reflectively, what an elephant's soul is like. The effect I

28:01.240 --> 28:05.700
desired was obtained, for he at once fell from his high horse and became a child again.

28:06.560 --> 28:12.680
I don't want an elephant's soul, or any soul at all, he said. For a few moments he sat despondently.

28:14.160 --> 28:18.520
Suddenly he jumped to his feet, with his eyes blazing and all the signs of intense cerebral

28:18.520 --> 28:24.740
excitement. To hell with you and your souls, he shouted. Why do you plague me about souls?

28:24.880 --> 28:29.140
Haven't I got enough to worry and pain to distract me already without thinking of souls?

28:29.780 --> 28:33.600
He looked so hostile that I thought he was in for another homicidal fit,

28:33.700 --> 28:39.740
so I blew my whistle. The instant, however, that I did so, he became calm and said apologetically,

28:40.600 --> 28:46.640
forgive me, doctor, I forgot myself. You do not need any help. I am so worried in my mind that

28:46.640 --> 28:52.480
I am apt to be irritable. If you only knew the problem I have to face, and that I am working out,

28:52.840 --> 28:58.240
you would pity and tolerate and pardon me. Pray do not put me in a straight waistcoat.

28:58.880 --> 29:04.580
I want to think, and I cannot think freely when my body is confined. I am sure you will understand.

29:05.880 --> 29:11.080
He had, evidently, self-control. So when the attendants came, I told them not to mind,

29:11.200 --> 29:17.100
and they withdrew. Renfield watched them go. When the door was closed, he said,

29:17.180 --> 29:23.480
with considerable dignity and sweetness, Dr. Seward, you have been very considerate towards me.

29:24.340 --> 29:27.760
Believe me that I am very, very grateful to you.

29:30.140 --> 29:36.320
I thought it well to leave him in this mood, and so I came away. There is certainly something to

29:36.320 --> 29:41.700
ponder over in this man's state. Several points seem to make what the American interviewer calls

29:41.700 --> 29:49.240
a story, if one could only get them in proper order. Here they are. Will not mention drinking.

29:49.900 --> 29:56.280
Fears the thought of being burdened with the soul of anything. Has no dread of wanting life

29:56.280 --> 30:03.600
in the future. Despises the meaner forms of life altogether, though he dreads being haunted by their

30:03.600 --> 30:10.900
souls. Logically, all these things point one way. He has assurance of some kind that he will acquire

30:10.900 --> 30:18.480
some higher life. He dreads the consequence, the burden of a soul. Then it is a human life he looks

30:18.480 --> 30:26.360
to. And the assurance? Merciful God, the count has been to him, and there is some new scheme of

30:26.360 --> 30:34.180
terror afoot. Later, I went after my round to Van Helsing and told him of my suspicion.

30:35.100 --> 30:40.040
He grew very grave, and after thinking the matter over for a while, he asked me to take him to

30:40.040 --> 30:46.780
Renfield. I did so. As we came to the door, we heard the lunatic within singing gaily,

30:47.280 --> 30:53.980
as he used to do in the time which now seems so long ago. When we entered, we saw with amazement

30:53.980 --> 30:59.380
that he had spread out his sugar as of old. The flies, lethargic with the autumn, were beginning

30:59.380 --> 31:05.000
to buzz into the room. We tried to make him talk of the subject of our previous conversation,

31:05.160 --> 31:11.180
but he would not attend. He went on with his singing, just as though we had not been present.

31:11.840 --> 31:18.020
He had got a scrap of paper and was folding it into a notebook. We had to come away as

31:18.020 --> 31:25.740
ignorant as we went in. His is a curious case indeed. We must watch him tonight.

31:29.540 --> 31:40.260
Letter, Mitchell, Sons and Candy, to Lord Godelming. 1st October. My Lord! We are at all times

31:40.260 --> 31:46.080
only too happy to meet your wishes. We beg, with regard to the desire of your lordship,

31:46.360 --> 31:51.680
expressed by Mr Harker on your behalf, to supply the following information concerning the sale

31:51.680 --> 31:59.800
and purchase of No. 347 Piccadilly. The original vendors are the executors of the late Mr Archibald

31:59.800 --> 32:06.640
Winter Suffield. The purchaser is a foreign nobleman, Count de Ville, who affected the

32:06.640 --> 32:11.560
purchase himself, paying the purchase money in notes, over the counter, if your lordship

32:11.560 --> 32:17.220
will pardon us using so vulgar an expression. Beyond this, we know nothing whatever of him.

32:17.820 --> 32:22.360
We are, my Lord, your lordship's humble servants, Mitchell, Sons and Candy.

32:25.180 --> 32:32.100
Dr Seward's Diary. 2nd October. I placed a man in the corridor last night, and told him to make

32:32.100 --> 32:36.920
an accurate note of any sound he might hear from Renfield's room, and gave him instructions that

32:36.920 --> 32:42.920
if there should be anything strange he was to call me. After dinner, when we had all gathered round

32:42.920 --> 32:48.660
the fire in the study, Mrs Harker having gone to bed, we discussed the attempts and discoveries

32:48.660 --> 32:54.880
of the day. Harker was the only one who had any result, and we are in great hopes that his clue

32:54.880 --> 33:00.520
may be an important one. Before going to bed, I went round to the patient's room and looked

33:00.520 --> 33:07.680
in through the observation trap. He was sleeping soundly. His heart rose and fell with regular

33:07.680 --> 33:13.720
respiration. This morning the man on duty reported to me that a little after midnight he was restless

33:13.720 --> 33:19.800
and kept saying his prayers somewhat loudly. I asked him if that was all. He replied that it

33:19.800 --> 33:25.100
was all he heard. There was something about his manner so suspicious that I asked him point blank

33:25.100 --> 33:30.420
if he had been asleep. He denied sleep, but admitted to having dozed for a while.

33:31.140 --> 33:34.440
It is too bad that men cannot be trusted unless they are watched.

33:36.420 --> 33:41.720
Today Harker is out following up his clue, and Art and Quincy are looking after horses.

33:43.500 --> 33:46.640
Godelming thinks that it would be well to have horses always in readiness,

33:47.720 --> 33:51.200
for when we get the information which we seek there will be no time to lose.

33:52.060 --> 33:58.160
We must sterilize all the imported earth between sunrise and sunset. We shall thus catch the count

33:58.160 --> 34:03.760
at his weakest, and without a refuge to fly to. Van Helsing is off to the British Museum,

34:04.320 --> 34:09.860
looking up some authorities on ancient medicine. The old physicians took account of things which

34:09.860 --> 34:15.100
their followers do not accept, and the professor is searching for witch and demon cures which may

34:15.100 --> 34:21.180
be useful to us later. I sometimes think we must be all mad and that we shall wake to sanity in

34:21.180 --> 34:29.900
straight waistcoats. Later we have met again. We seem at last to be on the track, and our work

34:29.900 --> 34:35.680
of tomorrow may be the beginning of the end. I wonder if Renfield's quiet has anything to do

34:35.680 --> 34:41.200
with this. His moods have so followed the doings of the count that the coming destruction of the

34:41.200 --> 34:47.520
monster may be carried to him some subtle way. If we could only get some hint as to what passed

34:47.520 --> 34:52.560
in his mind between the time of my argument with him today and his resumption of fly-catching,

34:53.380 --> 34:58.320
it might afford us a valuable clue. He is now seemingly quiet for a spell.

34:59.400 --> 35:05.080
Is he? That wild yell seemed to come from his room. The attendant came bursting into my room

35:05.080 --> 35:09.820
and told me that Renfield had somehow met with some accident. He had heard him yell,

35:10.000 --> 35:14.960
and when he went to him found him lying on his face on the floor, all covered with blood.

35:14.960 --> 35:16.940
I must go at once.

35:19.960 --> 35:21.600
End of chapter 20

